# ADR-0014 — Multi-Agent Orchestration Model

- Status: Accepted
- Date: 2026-07-19
- Deciders: Pharos Architecture Team

---

# Context

As the AI Operating System grows, a single Agent becomes insufficient for
handling complex tasks.

Real-world requests often require expertise from multiple domains.

Examples:

- software engineering
- marketing
- legal review
- finance
- product management
- customer support

Combining all responsibilities into a single Agent would create a large,
difficult-to-maintain component with conflicting objectives.

The system requires a collaborative execution model.

---

# Decision

The platform shall support multiple specialized Agents.

Each Agent owns one domain of expertise.

A request may involve one or more Agents.

```
User
   │
   ▼
Coordinator Agent
   │
   ├──────────────┐
   ▼              ▼
Engineering     Marketing
Agent           Agent
   │              │
   └──────┬───────┘
          ▼
      Runtime
```

Agents collaborate.

Runtime executes.

---

# Agent Roles

Every Agent has a clearly defined responsibility.

Examples:

- CEO Agent
- Engineering Agent
- Marketing Agent
- Sales Agent
- Finance Agent
- Legal Agent
- Product Agent
- Customer Success Agent

No Agent should become responsible for unrelated domains.

---

# Coordinator Agent

The Coordinator Agent is responsible for orchestration.

Responsibilities include:

- understanding user requests
- decomposing work
- selecting appropriate Agents
- combining results
- resolving conflicts
- producing the final response

The Coordinator performs no execution.

---

# Specialist Agents

Specialist Agents:

- reason within their own domain
- retrieve domain knowledge
- use memory
- generate RuntimeIntent

They never execute work directly.

Execution always belongs to Runtime.

---

# Runtime Responsibilities

Runtime remains completely unaware of:

- Agent identities
- Agent hierarchy
- Agent collaboration

Runtime receives RuntimeIntent.

Nothing more.

---

# Agent Communication

Agents communicate through structured messages.

They do not invoke each other's internal implementations.

Possible message types include:

- request
- response
- delegation
- clarification
- review

Communication should remain implementation-independent.

---

# Knowledge Ownership

Every Agent may have access to different knowledge.

Examples:

Engineering Agent:

- ADRs
- architecture
- source code

Marketing Agent:

- campaigns
- branding
- market research

Legal Agent:

- regulations
- contracts
- compliance

Knowledge access is domain-specific.

---

# Memory Ownership

Each Agent maintains its own reasoning context.

Shared memory may exist but is not required.

Agents should avoid mutating another Agent's memory directly.

---

# Dependency Rules

Agents never depend on Runtime implementations.

Runtime never depends on Agents.

Agents communicate only through contracts.

Specialist Agents never coordinate execution.

Coordinator Agent never performs execution.

---

# Architectural Principles

## Domain Specialization

One Agent.

One domain.

One responsibility.

---

## Independent Evolution

Each Agent evolves independently.

Adding a new Agent should not require modifying existing Agents.

---

## Replaceable Agents

Any Agent implementation may be replaced without changing Runtime.

Examples:

EngineeringAgentV1

↓

EngineeringAgentV2

↓

EngineeringLLMAgent

---

## Stateless Runtime

Runtime remains identical regardless of the number of Agents.

---

# Alternatives Considered

## Single Universal Agent

Rejected.

Too many responsibilities.

Poor scalability.

Difficult testing.

---

## Runtime coordinates Agents

Rejected.

Coordination belongs to intelligence.

Execution belongs to Runtime.

---

## Agents execute Tools directly

Rejected.

Execution must remain centralized.

---

# Consequences

Positive:

- domain specialization
- scalable architecture
- independent evolution
- cleaner prompts
- easier testing
- future autonomous collaboration

Negative:

- additional orchestration layer
- more message passing
- increased architectural complexity

The long-term benefits justify the complexity.

---

# Future Evolution

Future versions may support:

- dynamic Agent discovery
- Agent capability negotiation
- hierarchical delegation
- peer-to-peer collaboration
- voting and consensus
- self-critique
- autonomous planning
- distributed Agent execution

The Runtime Core remains unchanged.

